comment: Unlike what I observed in the UK Court proceedings, our Courts allow judges much less discretion. We have Rules of Procedure that apply. There are Court rules that apply. There are the Rules of Evidence. I was distressed to see the level of judicial discretion allowed in the UK case where they have a system of writing these statements and the statements are submitted to court (Amber had 7....weird and kind of outrageous!) and then they are cross-examined with nothing but leading statements from the solicitor and solicitor-imposed suppositions about what was said/done/meant. That struck me as weird. That element of the UK judicial system surprised me....pretty wide open judicial discretion allowed Judge Nicol to do what he did and undermine justice. This judge (Judge White) seems to be fair, though. Remember Adam Waldman getting kicked off the case for leaking info under seal? That is a serious deal for a lawyer. It can implicate potential malpractice AND ethical situations involving violation of Attorney's Oath.  I am wondering if Waldman is now fighting off a bar complaint of some sort bc that can happen in the wake of these things.

comment:
I actually think the Judge's initial response to the Heard donations is very narrow-minded.  The point of the premise to not clout up the record is so you don't go through banal individual instances where the defendant lied which may not accurately represent the individual.  In this instance, if Amber Heard lied, it would be four-fold. 
1) She has used the lie to maintain the credibility of good character which was then used to substantiate her claims about abuse.  This directly correlates with the trial and the notion that Heard's perceived "good character" played a role in how her accusations were received, as well as damages to JD.  
2) This is not a single individual instance of a lie, but a maintained instance of a lie in a public forum.  It's not like she had an argument about it with JD once and that was it.  She made the claims publically to establish a good public will and to establish that the divorce was not due to financial reasons.  
3)Her divorce and relationship with JD is directly related to her accusations.  By implying that her divorce had no financial reasons behind it also implies a heavier burden of importance on the personal reasons for the divorce...which would be the "abuse."  This would not only be relevant to any argument regarding the Sun's publication (in the previous trial), but it would also play a role in how people would perceive her and her accusations (as it would further add to a history of problems).
4)Due to the magnitude of the lie, as well as the intentions of such a lie, it would clearly establish character reputation and truthfulness which, in a hearsay case, is incredibly important.  Establishing a history of manipulation and lying to further one's own ends is certainly a topic that should be looked into. 

4 good reasons why the judge should require heard to present her financials regarding the "donation."  Also, the idea that this would frighten the public from making donations is ludicrous and, quite frankly, a stupid assertion on many different levels.  I'm pretty sure the IRS would have no qualms calling this guy out for making such asinine logic.
